Creating images with R

With a little bit of magick

Rudy Begman

2023-03-13

My Meme

I saw this meme and it made me chuckle so i chose to use the same kind of layout but change the pic to Stitch instead of the child in the original meme to make it more my own.

library(magick)

#creates a meme

#create blank square then add text
white_square <- image_blank(width = 350, height = 60, color = "white") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Me: I'm gonna start eating healthy \n Also Me:\n", size = 20)

#load image
stitch_image <- image_read(path = "Stitch.jpeg")%>%
  image_scale(350)

#combine both images together
meme <- c(white_square, stitch_image)%>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE)

#create the meme
meme

#save as .png
image_write(meme, "my_first_meme.png")

My Animated Gif

I saw a meme which consisted of several images so i decided to recreate it as a gif. It was only after i finished that i realised that i needed another image in my gif so i put Stitch in as an introductory image.

library(magick)
#creates a gif

#When making this gif i use both pipes and nesting to help myself get used to both types of coding.

#intro slide
intro <- image_read ("Smiley stitch.jpg") %>% 
  image_scale (300) %>% 
    image_annotate (text = "My First \nGif", size = 40, gravity = "north")

# First slide
first_text <- image_blank(width = 300, height = 50, color = "white") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Mozart", gravity = "north", size = 40)
pic_1 <- image_read ("Mozart.jpg") %>%
  image_scale (300)
mozart <- c (pic_1, first_text) %>%
      image_append (stack = TRUE)

# Second Slide
second_text <- image_blank(width = 300, height = 50, color = "white") %>%
  image_annotate(text = "Cinderella", gravity = "north", size = 40)
pic_2 <- image_read ("Cinderella.webp") %>%
  image_scale (300)
cinderella <- c (pic_2, second_text) %>%
  image_append (stack = TRUE)

# Third Slide
half_cinderella <- image_crop (pic_2, geometry_area(150, 250, 130))
half_mozart <- image_crop (pic_1, geometry_area(150, 250, 50))
pic_3 <- image_append ( c(half_mozart, half_cinderella)) 
pic_4 <- image_read("Mozarella.jpg") %>%
  image_scale(300)
mozarella <- c (pic_3, pic_4) %>% 
  image_append (stack = TRUE)

# Create Gif
gif <- c (intro, mozart, cinderella, mozarella) %>%
  image_animate (delay = 150)

# Save Gif
image_write(gif, "my_first_gif.gif")

# Run Gif
gif
